Mockito, testing in isolation.

Often the code you want to test depends on something heavy and awkward: a database, a remote service, or the system clock. You do not want your unit test to actually need a real database. Mockito solves this. It lets you substitute a fake implementation of a dependency, one that returns exactly whatever you tell it to, and it lets you assert afterwards which methods were called on that fake.

The pattern reads almost like English. You call mock, passing the interface you want to fake, and you get back a mock object whose methods all return harmless defaults until you say otherwise. You then stub specific behaviour: when the repository's find-by-I-D is called with one, then return this particular user. You construct the real object under test, handing it the mock as its dependency. You assert on the result as usual. And then you verify interactions: verify that find-by-I-D was actually called with one, and verify, with never, that save was not called at all.

The core vocabulary is small. Mock creates the fake. When-then-return, and when-then-throw, define what stubbed calls do. Verify asserts that a call happened, and with times-n or never you assert exactly how many times. And argument matchers like any, any-long, and e-q let you be precise or flexible about the arguments you are matching. Under the hood, Mockito generates a subclass of your type at runtime and records every call, which is, once again, reflection at work. Put it together, and the combination of JUnit five, Mockito, and Assert-J is the testing stack you will find in essentially every modern Spring project.
